commit.message:
tests: Relax unnecessarily-strict constraint

Debian's parted package carries a patch to apply alignment constraints
to new partitions created on fresh disks.  This caused
`tests.test__ped_partition.PartitionMSDOSTypeIDTestCase.runTest` to fail
as follows:

  _ped.PartitionException: Unable to satisfy all constraints on the partition.

While I realize that a Debian patch isn't strictly upstream's problem,
in this case the optimal alignment constraint doesn't seem to have
anything to do with what's actually being tested, so relax it to a
minimal alignment constraint.

New version

Signed-off-by: David Cantrell <dcantrell@redhat.com>

Help the _ped module garbage collection in the test suite

This showed up starting with Python 3.12, but the test suite was
segfaulting inconsistently and it looked to be tied to Python's
garbage collection routines.  The _ped module is written with garbage
collection support so in order to more explicitly assist Python with
the reference counting, set objects to None when we are done with them
in the test suite base classes.

Confirmed this works for both Python 3.11 and 3.12, so hopefully this
is good now.  This took an inordinate amount of time to track down and
I do not wish to do it again.  Famous last words, I guess.

Signed-off-by: David Cantrell <dcantrell@redhat.com>

Signed-off-by: David Cantrell <dcantrell@redhat.com>

Replace outdated Red Hat sample GPLv2+ boilerplates

When I started pyparted, Red Hat provided a set of templates to use
for license boilerplate text in source files.  I took this and used it
in this project, which is GPLv2+.  To me I thought it was just the
standard GPL boilerplate with the addition of "Red Hat Author(s)" to
indicate that Red Hat contributed to this project.  But upon closer
inspection, I see Red Hat added a clause about company trademarks
which has nothing to do with the software license.

At this point in time, Red Hat does not provide any such template and
discourages the use of long standing common GPL boilerplate text.
Instead preferring very simple comments like this:

    Copyright The PROJECT Authors
    SPDX-License-Identifier: SPDX-ID

You should also include an AUTHORS file for reference, but it's also
ok to not do that since the information is in the git project history.
It is not necessary to list each contributor as an author in the files
themselves.  Note the actual copyright statement is simply "Copyright
NAME".  There is no year, years, or year range specified.  There's
also no "(c)" or "(C)".  These are not necessary and legend has it
they showed up to make copyright statements look "more official".
Copyright statements just need to use the word Copyright, Copr., or
the © symbol.  I chose the word Copyright because it is very easily
displayable in a wide range of editors.  It is also worth noting here
that "(c)" and "(C)" are not valid replacements for the © symbol.

For more information:
    https://matija.suklje.name/how-and-why-to-properly-write-copyright-statements-in-your-code
    https://www.linuxfoundation.org/blog/blog/copyright-notices-in-open-source-software-projects

tests: Add PARTITION_LINUX_HOME to flag tests

Add support for no_automount partition flag

This flag sets a GPT attribute bit on the partition and is used to
prevent automounting by Microsoft and the Discoverable Partition
Specification applications (eg. systemd).

Add new disk types - disk uuid and partition uuid

libparted now supports retrieving the disk and partition uuid values,
this adds support for the disk type flags, and fixes up the tests to
include them.

tests: Remove feature values from DiskTypeStrTestCase

These inevitably cause pyparted to fail when built against a new version
of parted. They don't provide any additional validation, other tests
already check for the expected features.

Add tests for high level partition type ID / UUID

These tests validate the high level API changes for handling
the partition type ID and UUID properties.

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>

Add tests for low level partition type ID / UUID

These tests validate the low level API changes for handling
the partition type ID and UUID properties.

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>

Add test base class helper for re-opening the device

It is useful to validate that changes made in the tests
persist correctly and can be reloaded. Adding a 'reopen'
helper method will allow reuse of this common pattern

Add test base class for GPT partitions

Fix start sector for test partition

The MSDOS partitions need to start at sector 1, not 0,
otherwise parted will throw an error about having a
recursive partition table when re-loading the disk.

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>

Add example for viewing and changing GPT partition type UUID

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>

This allows users to run the examples without having to
edit the source to change the path.

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>

Add type ID / UUID to partition dump example

Since the constants are conditionally exposed based on
the parted version built against, we need hasattr checks
to keep compatible.

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>

Map partition type ID / UUID accessors to Partition class

This adds 'type_uuid' and 'type_id' properties to the
Partition class.

Since the low level APIs are conditionally exposed based on
what parted version we build against, the high level APIs
raise a NotImplementedError for old parted.

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>

Bind low level APIs for type ID and UUID accessors

This binds the new methods:

  ped_partition_get_type_id
  ped_partition_set_type_id
  ped_partition_get_type_uuid
  ped_partition_set_type_uuid

There is no obvious compile time version info in the parted
headers that can be used to conditionalize the API usage.
Thus the code uses the PED_DISK_TYPE constants as a witness
for the APIs existing, on the basis that both were introduced
to the parted API concurrently.

Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrangé <berrange@redhat.com>
